Teach your family about cybersecurity topic of your choice.

This activity highlights the importance of cybersecurity awareness, as many attacks target human behaviour rather than technical systems.

I taught my family about phishing, which is one of the most common cybersecurity threats. I explained to them that phishing is when
scammers try to trick people into giving personal information like passwords or bank details by pretending to be a trusted organisation 
such as a bank or a delivery service.

To make it easier to understand, I gave real-life examples like fake messages saying “your parcel is delayed” or 
emails asking to reset a password. I showed them how to identify phishing by looking for signs such as spelling mistakes, unknown senders, suspicious links, and messages that create urgency.

I also explained what they should do if they receive such messages. I told them not to click on unknown links, 
not to share personal information, and to always verify the source before taking any action. I encouraged them to ask me
if they are unsure about any message.

This activity helped my family become more aware of online scams and how to stay safe. It also improved my
own understanding of cybersecurity, as teaching others made me realise how important awareness is in preventing cyberattacks.
